    <name>
      <text>Finding a Hyperbola with Given Foci and Asymptotes</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p> Find the hyperbola with foci \( F_{1} ({@focus1_x@}, {@focus1_y@})\) and  \( F_{1} ({@focus2_x@}, {@focus2_y@})\) and asymptotes \( (l_{{@asym_y@},{@coef@}}): {@asym@}  \).</p>
<p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p><b><h3>Worked solution</h3></b></p>
<p>We need to find the equation of the hyperbola with foci \( F_{1} ({@focus1_x@}, {@focus1_y@})\) and  \( F_{1} ({@focus2_x@}, {@focus2_y@})\) and asymptotes \( (l_{{@asym_y@},{@coef@}}): {@asym@}  \).
<br> The equation of a hyperbola opening left and right in standard form follows: \(\displaystyle  \frac{(x-h)^2}{a^2}- \frac{(y-k)^2}{b^2}=1.\)
<br> Here the center is \((h, k)\) and the vertices are \( (h \pm a, k) \)
<br> Let \(F_{1} (x_{F_{1}}, y_{F_{1}})\) and \(F_{2} (x_{F_{2}}, y_{F_{2}}) \) be the foci, and \( (l): y - y_{0} = \pm u (x-x_{0}) \) the asymptotes, we have \(F_{1}F_{2}=2\cdot c\). Then we have the following relations:
<br>\(
(1) \left\{ \begin{array}{r}
a^2+b^2= c^2\\ 
b= u \cdot a
\end{array}\right. \) 
 and \( (2) \left\{ \begin{array}{r}
h=  \displaystyle \frac{x_{F_{1}}+x_{F_{2}}}{2}\\ 
k=  \displaystyle \frac{y_{F_{1}}+y_{F_{2}}}{2}
\end{array}\right. \) 
<br> In this case, foci are \( F_{1} ({@focus1_x@}, {@focus1_y@})\) and  \( F_{1} ({@focus2_x@}, {@focus2_y@})\), and asymptotes \( (l_{{@asym_y@},{@coef@}}): {@asym@}  \), 
<br>Using the information above we have
<br> \( u = {@coef@}  \implies  b=  {@coef@}  \cdot a \)
<br> \(2 \cdot c =|x_{F_{1}}-x_{F_{2}}|=|({@focus1_x@})-({@focus2_x@})|={@cc@} \implies c = {@c@}\).
<br> The system (1) becomes: <br>\(
(1) \left\{ \begin{array}{r}
a^2+b^2= {@c^2@}\\ 
b= {@coef@} \cdot a
\end{array}\right. \implies 
\left\{ \begin{array}{r}
a=  \displaystyle {@val_a@}\\ 
b=  \displaystyle {@val_b@}
\end{array}\right.\) 
<br> Using the system (2), we get 
\( \left\{ \begin{array}{r}
h=  \displaystyle \frac{({@focus1_x@})+({@focus2_x@})}{2} = {@h@} \\ 
k=  \displaystyle \frac{({@focus1_y@})+({@focus2_y@})}{2} = {@k@}
\end{array}\right. \) 
<br> Therefore, the equation of the hyperbola is:
<br> \(  \displaystyle \frac{(x-({@h@}))^2}{@val_a^2@} - \frac{(y-({@k@}))^2}{@val_b^2@} = 1\)
<br> \( \displaystyle {@hyper2@} \)
<br> \( {@ta1@} \)]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
